Patterns in the Juan Fernandez fur seal faecal microbiome: R script 3

Constanza Toro

This is script number 3 of a series of html files containing all the code used for the statistical analysis of "Patterns in the Juan Fernandez fur seal (Arctophoca philippii philippii) faecal microbiome". The direct outputs of this analysis were the object generated with Script 1 located in the R_code folder within this GitHub repository. This script aims to look at betadiversity, correlations and genus abundance difference.

This script includes the following sections:
Note: files needed to run this coded were generated in section 4 of Script 1
1. Betadiversity
1.1. Principal coordinate analysis (PCoA)
1.1.1. Bray curtis
1.1.1.1. Full data
1.1.1.2. Core data
1.1.2. Weighted Unifrac
1.1.2.1. Full data
1.1.2.2. Core data
1.2. Clusters exploration 1.3. Hypothesis testing 5. Similarity Percentages analysis (SIMPER) 6. Correlation Analysis

 

  • Load libraries
library(tidyverse)
library(vegan)
library(ape)
library(kableExtra)

 

  • Load metadata
    Note: using rarefied data
# Full meta
read.csv("F2meta.csv") -> JFFS.meta
# Full rarefied ASV matrix
read.csv("ASV.RF.csv", 
         row.names = 1, 
         check.names = FALSE) -> ASV.RF

# Core meta
read.csv("F2coremeta.csv") -> core.meta
# Core rarefied ASV matrix
read.csv("ASV.RC.csv",
         row.names = 1,
         check.names = FALSE) -> ASV.RC

 

1. Betadiversity analysis

Beta-diversity is the rate of change in species composition from one community to another along gradients. Rarefied full and core data will be used.

 

1.1 Principal coordinate analysis (exploratory)

1.1.1 Bray curtis

1.1.1.1 Full rarefied dataset

  • Calculate a Bray-Curtis matrix and run PCoA
# Calculate a  Bray-Curtis distance matrix. Note that vegan requires n x m matrix of n samples and m variables. 
vegdist(ASV.RF, 
        method = "bray") -> dist_RF 

pcoa(dist_RF) -> PCoA_RF

 

Figure 1: Eigen values plot

barplot(PCoA_RF$values$Relative_eig[1:10])
About 35% of the variation is explained by the first two principal components.

 

Figure 2: PCoA using Bray-Curtis dissimilarity distance matrix

# Extract the first 2 PCs
PCOAaxes <- PCoA_RF$vectors[,c(1,2)]
colnames(PCOAaxes) = c("AxisBC_1", "AxisBC_2")

# Add to metadata 
cbind(JFFS.meta, PCOAaxes) -> JFFS.meta

#plot
ggplot(JFFS.meta,
       aes(AxisBC_1,
           AxisBC_2,
           color = Location,
           fill = Location)) +
  geom_point(size = 4) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
  scale_colour_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
  theme_bw() +
  xlab("PC1 (23.9%)") +
  ylab("PC2 (11.1%)") +
  labs(title = "PC0A on Bray-curtis dissimilarity distance",
       subtitle = "Filtered rarefied full microbiome") +
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank())
Bray Curtis quantifies the compositional dissimilarity between groups. Samples do not cluster based on location. However, it is possible to differentiate two clusters (top-left and bottom right). For the final image, a new cluster label will be added.

1.2 Clusters exploration

  • Load metadata
    Note: using non-rarefied data
# Filtered non-rarefied ASV_tax relative abundance
# Data in proportions
read.csv("ASV_taxcomp.csv", 
         row.names = 1, 
         check.names = FALSE) -> ASV_taxacomp

 

  • Prepare data and table
# Filtered phyla
dplyr::select(ASV_taxacomp,
              -"ASV",
              -"Kingdom",
              -"Family",
              -"Class",
              -"Genus",
              -"Order",
              -"Species") -> ASV_phyl

# Agregate to phyla
aggregate(ASV_phyl[1:54], 
          by = list(ASV_phyl$Phylum), 
          FUN = sum) -> ASV_phyl

# Add rownames
rownames(ASV_phyl) <- ASV_phyl[,1]

# Transpose
as.data.frame(t(ASV_phyl[,-1])) -> phyl

# Get clusters
# Cluster 1
# Get list
JFFS.meta %>%
  filter(BC_clus == "clus1") %>%
  droplevels() %>%
  pull(label) -> C1

# Filter
as.data.frame(t(phyl %>%
                  filter(rownames(phyl) %in% C1))) -> phyl1

# Summary
round(rowMeans(phyl1), 4)*100 -> phyl1$mean
round(apply(phyl1[,1:11], 1, sd), 4)*100 -> phyl1$SD

# Select columns and filter phyla with relative abundace > 1%
phyl1 %>%
  rownames_to_column("Phylum") %>%
  dplyr::select(Phylum, mean, SD) %>%
  filter(mean > 1) %>%
  mutate(Cluster = c(rep("clus1", 5))) -> phyl1


# Cluster 2
# Get list
JFFS.meta %>%
  filter(BC_clus == "clus2") %>%
  droplevels() %>%
  pull(label) -> C2

# Filter
as.data.frame(t(phyl %>%
                  filter(rownames(phyl) %in% C2))) -> phyl2

# Summary
round(rowMeans(phyl2), 4)*100 -> phyl2$mean
round(apply(phyl2[,1:11], 1, sd), 4)*100 -> phyl2$SD

# Select columns and filter phyla with relative abundace > 1%
phyl2 %>%
  rownames_to_column("Phylum") %>%
  dplyr::select(Phylum, mean, SD) %>%
  filter(mean > 1) %>%
  mutate(Cluster = c(rep("clus2", 5))) -> phyl2

# Combine tables
rbind(phyl1, phyl2) -> phyls

 

Figure 10: Comparison of relative abundance at the phylum level among clusters In Manuscript: Figure 5

phyls %>%
ggplot(aes(x=reorder(Phylum, 
                     mean),
                       y = mean, 
                       fill = Cluster)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", 
           position = position_dodge()) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = mean - SD, 
                    ymax = mean + SD), 
                width=.2,
                position=position_dodge(.9)) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Blues") +

                                 keyheight = 1)) +
  labs(title = "Comparison of relative abundance at the phylum level among clusters",
       subtitle = "Filtered non-rarefied dataset")
The ordination analysis revealed a consistent clusterisation pattern. This plot compared the relative abundance between the two clusters at the phylum level. The differences between the two clusters are consistent even at this higher taxonomic level.

 

1.3. Hypothesis testing

Based on the previous results, the hypothesis that cluster 1 is different to cluster 2 will be tested
### 1.3.1 Permutational Multivariate Analysis of Variance (PERMANOVA)
Null hypothesis: There is no difference in either within or between group Bray-Curtis distance for any of the clusters
-PERMANOVA using Bray-Curtis (filtered rarefied full dataset)

set.seed(123)
adonis(as.matrix(dist_RF) ~ BC_clus, 
       data = JFFS.meta,
       permutations = 999)

5. SIMPER at the Genus level Note. Using rarefied core data

To explore how genera differ between clusters, SIMPER analysis will be use to calculate the contribution of each genus (%) to the dissimilarity between each two cluster.
- load data Note. Using rarefied core data

read.csv("tax_FR.csv", 
         row.names = 1, 
         check.names = FALSE) -> tax_RC

 

  • Prepare data
# Full data
# Combine taxa with ASV Table
# Trasform matrix to data fram
as.data.frame(t(ASV.RC)) -> ASVRC

as.data.frame(tax_RC) -> taxRC

# combine
merge(ASVRC, 
      taxRC, 
      by = "row.names") -> ASV_taxRC

# Select samples and genus columns  
dplyr::select(ASV_taxRC,
              -"Row.names",
              -"Kingdom",
              -"Family",
              -"Class",
              -"Phylum",
              -"Order",
              -"Species") -> Gen_RC

# Agregate to Genus
aggregate(Gen_RC[1:54], 
          by = list(Gen_RC$Genus), 
          FUN = sum) -> ASV_Gen_RC

# Add row names
rownames(ASV_Gen_RC) <- ASV_Gen_RC$Group.1

# As matrix, simper needs samples as rows
as.matrix(t(ASV_Gen_RC[,-1])) -> Gen_Mat

 

5.1. Run SIMPER

simper(Gen_Mat, 
       core.meta$BC_clus,
       permutations = 999)
## cumulative contributions of most influential species:
## 
## $clus2_clus1
##                Peptoclostridium                   Fusobacterium 
##                       0.2460116                       0.4901221 
##                     Bacteroides         Ruminococcaceae UCG-005 
##                       0.5859594                       0.6488404 
## [Ruminococcus] gauvreauii group 
##                       0.7015811
Five Genera contributed to 70% of the variation between clusters. Peptoclostridium and Fusobacterium only, Contributed to almost 50% of this variation.

# flattenCorrMatrix
# ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
# cormat : matrix of the correlation coefficients
# pmat : matrix of the correlation p-values
flattenCorrMatrix <- function(cormat, pmat) {
  ut <- upper.tri(cormat)
  data.frame(
    row = rownames(cormat)[row(cormat)[ut]],
    column = rownames(cormat)[col(cormat)[ut]],
    cor  =(cormat)[ut],
    p = pmat[ut]
  )
}
flattenCorrMatrix(Genus.corr$r, 
                  Genus.corr$P) -> corrtable
